            color: #0056b3;
        }
        label {
            display: block;
            margin-bottom: 8px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        input[type="email"] {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 12px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            border: 2px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 4px;
            box-sizing: border-box;
            font-size: 16px;
            transition: border-color 0.3s ease;
        }
        input[type="email"]:focus {
            outline: none;
            border-color: #007bff;
        }
        input.valid {
            border-color: #28a745; /* Green */
        }
        input.invalid {
            border-color: #dc3545; /* Red */
        }
        .validation-feedback {
            margin-top: -10px;
            margin-bottom: 15px;
            font-size: 0.9em;
            color: #666;
            min-height: 1.2em; /* Reserve space */
        }
        .explanation {
            background-color: #e9f7ff;
            border-left: 5px solid #007bff;
            padding: 20px;
            margin-top: 30px;
            border-radius: 4px;
        }
        .explanation h3 {
            color: #0056b3;
            margin-top: 0;
        }
        .explanation ul {
            list-style-type: disc;
            margin-left: 20px;
        }
        .explanation li {
            margin-bottom: 8px;
        }
        code {
            background-color: #eee;
            padding: 2px 4px;
            border-radius: 3px;
            font-family: monospace;
        }
        strong {
            color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Email Validation Demo (with Real-time Regex)</h1>

        <p>Type an email address into the field below to see real-time regex validation feedback.</p>

        <label for="emailInput">Email Address:</label>
        <input type="email" id="emailInput" placeholder="e.g., test@example.com">
        <div class="validation-feedback" id="feedbackMessage"></div>

        <div class="explanation">
            <h3>Why Regex is Fundamentally Limited for Email Validation (and Better Alternatives)</h3>

            <p>While regular expressions are powerful for pattern matching, they are inherently insufficient for fully validating email addresses according to the official RFC specifications. Here's why:</p>

            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>RFC Complexity:</strong> The official specifications (primarily <a href="https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5322" target="_blank">RFC 5322</a> and <a href="https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5321" target="_blank">RFC 5321</a>, along with others like RFC 6531 for internationalized domains) define a highly complex structure for email addresses. This includes:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Permitting various special characters (like <code>! # $ % & ' * + - / = ? ^ _ ` { | } ~</code>) in the local part (before the '@').</li>
                        <li>Allowing quoted strings and comments.</li>
                        <li>IP addresses as domains (e.g., <code>user@[192.168.1.1]</code>).</li>
                        <li>Internationalized Domain Names (IDNs) and Internationalized Email Addresses (IEAs) which allow non-ASCII characters.</li>
                    </ul>
                    A regex that attempts to capture all valid permutations would be incredibly long, unreadable, and still likely incomplete or prone to false positives/negatives.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>The "Perfect" Regex is a Myth:</strong> There are famous "perfect" email regexes (like the one by <a href="https://www.ex-parrot.com/~pdw/Mail-RFC822-Address.html" target="_blank">RFC 822 parser in Perl</a>) that are several kilobytes long. These are not practical for client-side validation and often still have subtle flaws or don't cover newer RFCs.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>What Regex <em>Can't</em> Validate:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Existence:</strong> A regex cannot tell you if an email address actually exists or has a valid mailbox.</li>
                        <li><strong>Reachability:</strong> It can't tell you if the domain's mail servers are configured correctly or if the recipient server will accept mail for that address.</li>
                        <li><strong>Typographical Errors:</strong> A regex might validate <code>john@gmial.com</code> as syntactically correct, but it's a typo for <code>gmail.com</code>.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Better Alternatives for Production Use:</h3>

            <p>Instead of relying solely on regex, a multi-layered approach is recommended for robust email validation:</p>

            <ol>
                <li>
                    <strong>Client-Side: HTML5 <code>type="email"</code> and Basic Regex:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Use <code>&lt;input type="email"&gt;</code>: This provides basic browser-level validation and a suitable keyboard for mobile users.</li>
                        <li>Use a simple, permissive regex (like the one in this demo) for immediate, user-friendly feedback. Its purpose is to catch obvious errors, not to be RFC-compliant. Aim for "good enough" rather than "perfect."</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Server-Side Validation with Libraries:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Always re-validate on the server.</strong> Client-side validation is for UX, server-side is for security and data integrity.</li>
                        <li>Use a well-maintained, battle-tested email validation library in your chosen backend language (e.g., <code>email-validator</code> in Python, <code>EmailValidator</code> in PHP, <code>validator.js</code> on Node.js, JavaMail for Java). These libraries often implement a more comprehensive (though still not fully exhaustive) set of RFC rules.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>DNS MX Record Lookup:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>On the server, after basic syntax validation, perform a DNS query for the Mail Exchange (MX) records of the domain part of the email address. If no MX records exist, it's highly unlikely to be a valid mail-receiving domain.</li>
                        <li>Be aware: Some legitimate domains might not have MX records (e.g., if they only send email but don't receive it directly, or use a CNAME for mail).</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>SMTP Verification (Advanced/Paid Services):</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>For critical applications, consider using a third-party email verification service. These services often perform a "simulated" SMTP handshake with the recipient's mail server to check if an email address actually exists without sending an email.</li>
                        <li>This is the most accurate method for determining deliverability but can be slow, costly, and sometimes blocked by mail servers.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Double Opt-in:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>The ultimate validation for user-provided email addresses. Send a confirmation email with a unique link that the user must click to verify their address. This proves the user owns the address and it is deliverable.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ol>

            <p>In summary, use a simple regex for immediate client-side feedback, but never rely on it alone. Combine it with robust server-side library validation, MX record checks, and ideally, a double opt-in process for maximum accuracy and deliverability.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
            const emailInput = document.getElementById('emailInput');
            const feedbackMessage = document.getElementById('feedbackMessage');

            // A common, relatively permissive regex for client-side email validation.
            // This is NOT RFC-compliant, but good for catching common errors and providing real-time feedback.
            // It broadly checks for:
            // - A local part (alphanumeric, some special chars, dots, hyphens)
            // - An '@' symbol
            // - A domain part (alphanumeric, dots, hyphens)
            // - A top-level domain (at least two letters/numbers)
            const emailRegex = new RegExp(
                /^(([^<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+(\.[^<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+)*)|(".+"))@((\[[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\])|(([a-zA-Z\-0-9]+\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,}))$/
            );

            emailInput.addEventListener('input', () => {
                const email = emailInput.value.trim();

                // Clear previous state
                emailInput.classList.remove('valid', 'invalid');
                feedbackMessage.textContent = '';

                if (email === '') {
                    feedbackMessage.textContent = 'Please enter an email address.';
                    return;
                }

                if (emailRegex.test(email)) {
                    emailInput.classList.add('valid');
                    feedbackMessage.textContent = 'Looks like a valid email format!';
                    feedbackMessage.style.color = '#28a745';
                } else {
                    emailInput.classList.add('invalid');
                    feedbackMessage.textContent = 'Invalid email format. Please check for typos.';
                    feedbackMessage.style.color = '#dc3545';
                }
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use This File:

1.  **Save:** Copy the entire code block above and save it as an `.html` file (e.g., `email_validation_demo.html`).
2.  **Open:** Open the saved HTML file in any web browser.

### Key Features and Explanations within the Code:

1.  **Real-time Feedback:** As you type, the input field's border will turn green for a "valid-looking" email and red for an "invalid-looking" email based on the regex. A message also appears below the input.
2.  **CSS Styling:** Basic CSS is included to make the form presentable and clearly show the green/red borders.
3.  **JavaScript Logic:**
    *   An `input` event listener is attached to the email field.
    *   A common, moderately complex regex is used for the client-side check. I've chosen one that's reasonably robust for common cases without being excessively long, but it's explicitly stated that it's *not* RFC-compliant.
    *   It adds/removes `valid` and `invalid` classes to the input field and updates a feedback message.
4.  **In-depth Explanation of Limitations:**
    *   The `div` with class `explanation` provides a detailed breakdown of why regex is insufficient for full RFC-compliant email validation.
    *   It highlights the complexity of RFCs, the mythical "perfect regex," and what regex fundamentally cannot validate (existence, deliverability, typos).
    *   **Crucially, it outlines a multi-layered approach for production use:**
        *   Client-side HTML5 `type="email"` and simple regex (for UX).
        *   **Server-side validation with libraries (essential!).**
        *   DNS MX record lookup.
        *   SMTP verification (advanced).
        *   Double opt-in (the gold standard).

### Why I Chose This Specific Regex for the Demo:

The regex used in the demo (`/^(([^<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+(\.[^<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+)*)|(".+"))@((\[[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\])|(([a-zA-Z\-0-9]+\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,}))$/`) is a widely adopted "sensible middle ground" for client-side JavaScript validation. It's not the shortest, nor the most complex, but it covers a good range of common, valid email formats while rejecting many common invalid ones.

**It's important to reiterate:** Even this regex, while good for client-side UX, does *not* fully comply with RFCs. For example, it doesn't handle comments, certain quoted local parts perfectly, or many obscure but technically valid email formats. This is precisely the point of the explanation section.

This file should give you a comprehensive understanding and a practical demonstration of email validation nuances!

That's a fantastic idea for a project and a great way to illustrate the limitations of regex for email validation! I'll create a single, self-contained HTML file for you that includes:

