### Explanation of the Regex Used:

```javascript
const emailRegex = new RegExp(
    /^(([^<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+(\.[^<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+)*)|(".+"))@((\[[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\])|(([a-zA-Z\-0-9]+\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,}))$/
);
```

This regex is a commonly used, pragmatic pattern for client-side email validation. It's more comprehensive than a very simple one but still not RFC-compliant. Here's a breakdown:

*   `^`: Start of the string.
*   `(([^<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+(\.[^<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+)*)|(".+"))`: This part handles the "local part" (the part before `@`).
    *   `([^<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+(\.[^<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+)*)`: Allows characters that are not angle brackets, parentheses, brackets, backslash, comma, semicolon, colon, space, at-sign, or double quote. It also allows multiple such sequences separated by dots.
    *   `|(".+")`: This `OR` condition allows for a quoted string (e.g., `"John Doe"@example.com`), which is technically valid but rare.
*   `@`: Matches the literal at-sign.
*   `((\[[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\])|(([a-zA-Z\-0-9]+\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,}))`: This handles the "domain part" (after `@`).
    *   `(\[[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\])`: Allows for an IP address literal enclosed in square brackets (e.g., `user@[192.168.1.1]`).
    *   `|`: OR
    *   `(([a-zA-Z\-0-9]+\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,})`: This is the more common domain format.
        *   `[a-zA-Z\-0-9]+`: One or more letters, numbers, or hyphens.
        *   `\.`: A literal dot.
        *   `(...)`: This pattern repeats one or more times (e.g., `example.com`, `sub.example.co.uk`).
        *   `[a-zA-Z]{2,}`: The top-level domain (TLD) must be at least two letters long.
*   `$`: End of the string.

